#English
bear_eng = "Grizzly Bears (Ursus arctos horribilis): The grizzly bear weighs 300 to 1,500 pounds and can stand up to 8 feet tall. They are able to run quite fast, reaching speeds up to 35 miles per hour. Wild bears are omnivores, and discover their food with their feeling of smell. They like to eat berries, rodents, roots, plant bulbs, cutworm moths, and whitebark pine nuts. Similarly, they also eat mountain sheep and goats, deer, moose, and elk. The wild bear invests a ton of energy looking for food and eating in the pre-fall and late-summer. Currently, Grizzly Bears in the United States are an endangered species that are at risk for extinction, with around 33,000 total in the United States."
lion_eng = "Lions (Panthera leo): Female lions often weigh anywhere from 240 lbs to 316 lbs, while male lions weigh anywhere from 350 lbs to 496 lbs. They are able to reach high speeds at around 50 miles per hour. Lions spend much of their time resting; they are inactive for about twenty hours per day. They spend an average of two hours a day walking and fifty minutes eating. They usually kill medium sized mammals, and often eat animals which have been killed by another hunter, such as hyenas. Its prey comprises chiefly of blue wildebeest, fields zebra, African bison, gemsbok and giraffe. Currently, lions are listed as “vulnerable” with fears of endangerment increasing."
flam_eng = 'Caribbean Flamingos (Phoenicopterus ruber): Caribbean Flamingos weigh up to 6 lbs, and stand at almost 5 feet. Their diets consist of small animals, including small shrimp and other crustaceans, mollusks, invertebrates like insects and larvae, and blue-green algae. In their youth, they have a grey coat, but eventually develop a pink/orange color as they grow older. They are mainly found near shallow bodies of water in the Caribbean, and mudflats. Population of the Caribbean Flamingo is anywhere from 850,000 and 880,000. Currently, they are not at risk for endangerment or extinction.'
panda_eng = 'Red Pandas (Ailurus fulgens): Red Pandas can weigh from 12 to 20 pound during their lifetime. They are omnivores, and their diets consist mostly of bamboo and select fruits and small insects. They reside in Asia (mostly China, Nepal and Myanmar), spending most of their time in trees. Currently, red pandas are endangered, with around 10,000 left in the world.'
